definition.value: An O-acyl carbohydrate that consists of any hexose substituted at position 6 by a sinapoyl group.
A 1,2-diacyl-sn-glycerol that has stearoyl and oleoyl as the 1- and 2-acyl groups respectively.

A 39-membered polypeptide consisting of His, Ser, Asp, Gly, Thr, Phe, Thr, Ser, Asp, Leu, Ser, Lys, Gln, Met, Glu, Glu, Glu, Ala, Val, Arg, Leu, Phe, Ile, Glu, Trp, Leu, Lys, Asn, Gly, Gly, Pro, Ser, Ser, Gly, Ala, Pro, Pro, Pro and Ser-NH2 residues joined in sequence. It is isolated from venom of the Gila monster lizard Heloderma horridum.
A  1,2-diacyl-sn-glycerol where icosanoyl and oleoyl are the 1- and 2-acyl groups respectively.
A 1,2-diacyl-sn-glycerol where linoleoyl and oleoyl form the 1- and 2-acyl groups respectively.
A  1,2-diacyl-sn-glycerol where arachidonoyl and oleoyl form the 1- and 2-acyl groups respectively.

A monocarboxylic acid amide obtained by formal condensation of the carboxy group of (2-nitro-1H-imidazol-1-yl)acetic acid with the amino group of ethanolamine. Used as a radiosensitising agent for hypoxic tumour cells.
A 2-monoglyceride where the acyl group is (9Z,12Z,15Z)-octadecatrienoyl (alpha-linolenoyl).
A 1,2-diacyl-sn-glycerol in which the 1- and 2-acyl groups are specified as oleoyl and alpha-linolenoyl respectively.
An Ins-1-P-Cer A(1-) in which the acyl group and the ceramide base contain a total of 34 carbons and 0 double bonds. Major species at pH 7.3.
An Ins-1-P-Cer A(1-) in which the acyl group and the ceramide base contain a total of 36 carbons and 0 double bonds. Major species at pH 7.3.
An Ins-1-P-Cer A(1-) in which the acyl group and the ceramide base contain a total of 38 carbons and 0 double bonds. Major species at pH 7.3.
An Ins-1-P-Cer A(1-) in which the acyl group and the ceramide base contain a total of 40 carbons and 0 double bonds. Major species at pH 7.3.
An Ins-1-P-Cer A(1-) in which the acyl group and the ceramide base contain a total of 42 carbons and 0 double bonds. Major species at pH 7.3.
An Ins-1-P-Cer A(1-) in which the acyl group and the ceramide base contain a total of 44 carbons and 0 double bonds. Major species at pH 7.3.
An Ins-1-P-Cer A(1-) in which the acyl group and the ceramide base contain a total of 46 carbons and 0 double bonds.
An organophosphate oxoanion obtained by deprotonation of the diphosphate OH groups of phytyl phosphate.
An oligopeptide comprising ten D-glutamic acid residues linked by peptidic bonds between the amino and gamma-carboxy groups.

A mannosylinositol phosphoceramide(1-) in which the acyl group is hydroxylated at position 2 and one other unspecified position while the ceramide base is hydroxylated at position 4. Major species at pH 7.3.
A phosphocholine that is the mono-1-elaidyl ester of phosphocholine
A cinnamate ester obtained by formal condensation of the carboxy group of cis-caffeic acid with the 5-hydroxy group of (+)-quinic acid.
An alpha-amino acid ester that is the methyl ester of N(gamma)-nitro-L-arginine.
A cinnamate ester obtained by formal condensation of the carboxy group of trans-caffeic acid with the 4-hydroxy group of (+)-quinic acid.
An aryl sulfate that is indoxyl sulfate in which the indole moiety is substituted at positions 4 and 5 by chlorine and bromine, respectively.
A cinnamate ester obtained by formal condensation of the carboxy group of sinapic acid with the 3-hydroxy group of (-)-quinic acid.
A hydroxamic acid obtained by formal condensation of the carboxy group of serine with the amino group of hydroxylamine.
An EC 6.1.1.* (ligases forming aminoacyl tRNA and related compounds) inhibitor that specifically inhibits the action of seryl-tRNA synthetase (EC 6.1.1.11).
A cinnamate ester obtained by formal condensation of the carboxy group of sinapic acid with the 4-hydroxy group of (-)-quinic acid.
A cinnamate ester obtained by formal condensation of the carboxy group of sinapic acid with the 5-hydroxy group of (-)-quinic acid.
A carboxylic ester obtained by formal condensation of the carboxy group of octanoic (caprylic) acid with the hydroxy group of 5-bromo-4-chloroindoxyl.
A cinnamate ester obtained by formal condensation of the carboxy group of 4-coumaric acid with the 3-hydroxy group of quinic acid.
A racemate comprising equimolar amounts of (R)- and (S)-nicardipine. It is a calcium channel blocker which is used to treat hypertension.
A cinnamate ester obtained by formal condensation of the carboxy group of 4-coumaric acid with the 5-hydroxy group of (-)-quinic acid.
An indolyl carbohydrate that is the alpha-D-mannoside of indoxyl in which the indole moiety is substituted at positions 4 and 5 by chlorine and bromine, respectively
An indolyl carbohydrate that is the alpha-D-glucoside of indoxyl in which the indole moiety is substituted at positions 4 and 5 by chlorine and bromine, respectively.
A 1-acyl-sn-glycerol that is the S-enantiomer of 2,3-dihydroxypropyl decanoate.
A glycoside resulting from the attachment of any pyranosyl group to a non-acyl group RO- (also RS-, RSe-, etc.).
A 1,2-diacyl-sn-glycerol in which the 1- and 2-acyl groups are specified as capryl (decanoyl) and oleoyl (9Z-octadecenoyl) respectively.
An indolyl carbohydrate that is the alpha-D-galactoside of indoxyl in which the indole moiety is substituted at positions 4 and 5 by chlorine and bromine, respectively.
Any alicyclic ketone resulting from the formal oxidation of the hydroxy group at position 3 of any pyranoside to the corresponding keto group.

An aryl phosphate that is indoxyl phopshate in which the indole moiety is substituted at positions 4 and 5 by chlorine and bromine, respectively. It is used to test for the presence of an enzyme, alkaline phosphatase, which cleaves the phosphate group to give 5-bromo-4-chloroindoxyl, which immediately dimerises to give an intensely blue product.
A glycosyloxyflavone that is chrysoeriol in which the hydroxyl hydrogen at position 7 is replaced by a 6-p-coumaroylglucosyl residue.
An indolyl carbohydrate that is the beta-D-glucuronide of indoxyl in which the indole moiety is substituted at positions 4 and 5 by chlorine and bromine, respectively
An indolyl carbohydrate that is the alpha-D-glucuronide of indoxyl in which the indole moiety is substituted at positions 4 and 5 by chlorine and bromine, respectively.
An indolyl carbohydrate that is the beta-D-glucosaminide of indoxyl in which the indole moiety is substituted at positions 4 and 5 by chlorine and bromine, respectively.
An indolyl carbohydrate that is the beta-D-galactosaminide of 3-hydroxy-1H-indole in which the indole moiety is substituted at positions 4 and 5 by chlorine and bromine, respectively.
A C-glycosyl compound that is isoorientin in which the hydroxyl hydrogen at position 7 is replaced by a glucosyl residue.
A C-glycosyl compound that is isoorientin in which the hydroxyl hydrogen at position 7 is replaced by an alpha-L-rhamnosyl-(1->2)-beta-D-glucosyl moiety.
A C-glycosyl compound that is isoorientin in which the hydroxyl hydrogen at position 7 is replaced by a 6-sinapoylglucosyl residue.
